While the exast words you referenced are not found <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>in the Constitution</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, but the very meaning is embedded in the very foundation of the United States. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=treeslover>Treeslover</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1880<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/7/03 2:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Freedom</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That we hold these Truths to be self-evident, that all Men are Created Equal, that they are Endowed by their Creator with certain Inalienable Rights, among these are Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Happiness - that to secure these Rights, Governments are instituted among Men, deriving their just Powers from the Consent of the Governed, that whenever any form of Government becomes destructive to these Ends, it is the Right of the People to alter or abolish it<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
  The Declaration of Independence is not something we base our laws on here in the United States, nor is any law liable to be upheld to the Declaration of Independence.  While it makes for great quotations, it doesn't have any legal basis.  The rights as are spelled out by the Constitution, the Bill of Rights and the subsequent amendments to the Constitution, which are the basis for our jurisprudence in the United States.  Nice quotes from Benjamin Franklin and Ann Rand (I'm sure it was ann since I've never heard of Any but I could be wrong) aside, they again bring no basis of law.  One can easily find an opposing viewpoint but that doesn't really lend any credibility to the argument.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>While the exast words you referenced are not found in the Constitution, but the very meaning is embedded in the very foundation of the United States.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
  I would disagree.  Our forefathers knew exactly what they were doing when they allowed for certain liberties, restricted others, and ultimately left the vast majority up to the states to decide.  You can not just toss words into their mouth because certain representitives of the convention were more liberal than others.  That goes against the very foundation of what the United States stands; Democracy.<br>
   <br>
  The founders worked long and hard and many disagreed on the exact wording that should be included in the document.  While scholars can debate what the individual founding fathers &quot;really&quot; meant, and court justices can detail for you interpretations of the constitution, ultimately it is up for each individual person to decide what it means, because in the end, your vote will decide matters.<br>
<br>
  To me, unreasonable search and seizure probably means considerably different than what you would consider it to be.  I personally have nothing to hide, if the police feel they can catch a drug dealer by taping my phone.  Go right ahead, mostly I just talk to telemarketers anyways, at least perhaps then I could provide more than myself with personal amusement in how I get rid of them.  <br>
<br>
  Why don't you read the non-bolded part in between your Jefferson quote and guess as to what the man meant.  Has our government reached the point where it becomes destructive to these ends?   I personally don't think so.  Do you?  At the moment it would seem the majority do not believe it's the case.  Perhaps that will change, perhaps not.  Perhaps our congressmen will modify the laws as the needs of the people change.  I'm not ready to go all fire and brimstone over this issues because at the moment, nor in the forseeable future do I see it becoming as Jefferson said, 'Destructive to these ends'.  <br>
